lso indicates long charm above and short charm below. So summing it all: long charm makes MMs longer delta as the expo comes, and this effects only accelerates, meaning they need to sell more and more $ES $ES_F above the zero speed line. Whenever it tries to fall below, MMs are shorter charm, putting them into shorter delta, forcing them to buyback futs. This traps the price and the increasing ATM long gamma at 5950 $SPX pins it as MMs are forced to sell the rips and buy the dips in increasing amount.\n What I mean by long skew/short skew... I already elaborated on this, but here it is: Skew is OTM put IV minus OTM call IV. I already explained that IV reflects supply and demand bcs of the risk premium. So whenever the customers long the skew they basically short risk reversal, meaning they long OTM puts and short OTM calls, putting MMs into short skew/long RR by shorting downside puts and longing upside calls. Of course, I\u0027m talking about net exposure. This means, the positioning is net longer upside gamma and vega, and net shorter downside gamma and vega, so this is long speed environment. And bcs long OTM call and short OTM put positions have negative charm and positive vanna, so will be the whole positioning structural flow as well. And this also means, MMs buying #volatility if spot moves down, and selling #volatility if price moves up, making spot/vol beta shorter (spot up/vol down), vega+gamma creates left-tail risk, as downside moves become more violent but also more instabile, and upside moves are sustained, vol compressing (as there is more liquidity) but more stable, and they getting shorter vanna longer charm beyond certain lvls into both direction.\n If customer positioning is net short OTM puts and long OTM calls (long RR), they essentially short the skew, putting MMs into long skew by longing OTM puts and shorting OTM calls. This means, the net MM exposure is shorter upside gamma and vega and longer downside gamma and vega, that is a short speed environment, also meaning MMs are buying #volatility if spot moves up, and selling #volatility if spot moves down, this makes spot/vol beta longer (spot up/vol up) creating right-tail risk, as upside moves are potentially more violent with increased vol, and downside moves are more stable with decreased vol increased liquidity. This also puts MMs into net long charm and short vanna, and they become longer vanna, shorter charm beyond certain lvls into any direction.\nZero vanna? Zero speed lvl is similar like standing in the middle of a butterfly spread. In this case it is like a short butterfly middle-point. Now imagine, if you #volatility starts to increase, the upside deltas will come down (short vanna), and downside deltas will increase (long vanna), vega also increases, and Gamma approaches zero, and gamma also decreases (short gamma), and vanna will approach zero as well, so is charm. Meaning the position converges towards an ATM straddle from attribute perspective where vanna is zero. Bcs of zomma and color effect the zero speed line changes dynamically . And when vol events occur, this assuptions can predict the bottom lvls of the fall where the #market is structurally determined to fall, in a certain vol environment. This \"zero vanna\" lvl is what I\u0027m currently working on.\nFrom MM perspective it is the opposite. bcs if an MM portfolio is longer gamma to the upside and shorter gamma to the downside (positive speed), its like longing a risk reversal (long otm call, short otm put) as skew is otm put iv minus otm call iv, the long risk reversal is basically bet on the skew to dump, bcs it bids up the otm call iv, and sells the otm put iv and so the difference between otm put iv and otm call iv will be lower.. meaning skew down. so a long risk reversal trade is a short skew trade. and bcs long otm call has negative charm, and short otm put has also negative charm... you will have a negative charm exposure. and bcs long otm call has positive vanna, and short otm put also has positive vanna, you will have a net positive vanna exposure. so is longer color to the upside and shorter color to the downside, with zero color in the middle. This means, by the time you become shorter skew. and bcs both vanna and charm goes towards zero around the ATM strike, your short skew exposure will be shorter vanna and longer charm into any direction the spot moves. and an extra layer, just to make sure your head explodes is, that just like with gamma, you are longer vega to the upside (so you sell vol if price moves up), and shorter vega to the downside (so you buy vol if the price moves down). This is crucial, bcs higher vol means less liquidity (bcs supply and demand side has to \"look for each other more\" bcs the direction is one sided) so vol increases to the downside, meaning less stable momentum, creating left-tail risk. And vol decreases to the upside, so higher liquidity there (every seller finds a buyer and vice versa very fast), so momentum is more stable to the upside. If you long the skew, this is the exact opposite. Draw the delta, gamma, vega, vanna and charm curves to yourself and you gonna understand it You can gain a lot of extra informations from this... If MM has short charm exposure he will be shorter delta as time passes and forced to buy back futs\n"},{"ty":"as","st":"document","si":0,"ei":0,"sm":{"ds_pw":595.3,"ds_mt":70.85,"ds_lhs":1,"ds_mr":56.7,"ds_mb":56.7,"ds_rtd":"mso-rtd.0","ds_ulhfl":false,"ds_hi":"kix.upckxp11zttv","ds_ml":56.7,"ds_mh":35.4,"ds_ph":841.9,"ds_mf":35.4}},{"ty":"ae","et":"list","id":"kix.list.2","epm":{"le_nb":{"nl_4":{"b_gf":"%4","b_ts":{"ts_un":false,"ts_un_i":true,"ts_sc":false,"ts_it_i":true,"ts_fgc2":{"hclr_color":"#000000","clr_type":0},"ts_st_i":true,"ts_bgc2":{"hclr_color":null,"clr_type":0},"ts_fs_i":true,"ts_ff_i":false,"ts_bgc2_i":true,"ts_it":false,"ts_va":"nor","ts_bd_i":true,"ts_va_i":true,"ts_fs":11.0,"ts_ff":"Courier New","ts_st":false,"ts_bd":false,"ts_fgc2_i":true,"ts_sc_i":