the patterns. Think in curves You can have two kind of basic gamma profiles:\n·   \tNet negative speed convexity \u003d positive speed first then negative speed as we\u0027re going to the upside\n·   \tNet positive speed convexity \u003d negative speed first then positive speed as we\u0027re going to the upside\nWhen the territory has negative speed convexity, thats basically a long butterfly pattern, net positive speed convexity is short butterfly pattern. ...sampling the gamma exposure for the sake of simplifying the pattern... You can see below how vega and theta relates to gamma. If you invert the curve, the others will invert too, and so do their derivatives (like speed, vanna and charm). Long fly is a typicall high theta, premium burning, pinning structure, while short fly is a low theta, wider rangebounding, mean reverting environment. While zero speed helps me to find the long skew/short skew shifts, through zero vanna I can find the borderlines of these fly-patterns because (like a sine wave) long fly is followed by a short fly, and short fly is followed by a long fly. But the values are different. And using this we can understand what kind of stage is set for the price action by structural flows, and how the momentum would act if it would be totally determined only by dealer flows. Any deviation from this behaviour is an \u0027anomaly\u0027 caused by sentiment/momentum effects, that reveal the actual underlying flows of the market\nPs. Speed is simply the slope of the gamma curve. If speed steepens or not depends on color (gamma change in time). Color is charm convexity basically.\n*\n*\n*\n*\n\n \nSpotting out intraday reversals and why they coincidence or near to the lowest gamma lvls (+ zero speed \u0026 vanna again)... tl;dr bcs thats where vanna impact is the highest Speed is the first derivative of the gamma function, we call it as the rate of change in gamma relative to spot. First look at the premarket posted GEX chart The interesting part is this range: Don\u0027t be confused about \"local speed flip\", the \"zero speed\" lines I provide are net values.\nWhen MMs are positive speed, they are locally long vanna short charm, and when they are negative speed, they are locally short vanna, long charm. Imagine an inverted gamma curve: as you move down the spot (from right to left on the x-axis) you become shorter gamma, but eventually you gonna reach the lowest point from where you are longer gamma. Few months ago I wrote a post about gamma and #volatility inverse correlation. I wrote there, that bcs sigma (vol) is in the nominators of the gamma formula: the higher the #volatility goes, the lower the gamma becomes and vice versa. And this makes sense intuitively too, bcs long gamma tends to tighten the range of returns as MMs delta hedge against the price momentums, and short gamma widens the range of returns as MMs delta hedge into the directions of the price moves.\nWhat this means is that as the price went lower, the shorter the MM gamma became. They didn\u0027t necessary go negative, but they had less and less gamma exposure on the way down, so they had to buy against the trend less and less, that both mathematically and naturally increases the #volatility. And then the momentum reached a point where gamma impact was near to zero and even turned into negative. And this is where things get interesting...\nWhat is vanna? Vanna is the derivative of the vega, the rate of change in vega relative to spot, and so it measures the delta change to vol too. Now, bcs vomma is zero at ATM and peaks around 20-25 and 70-75 deltas, if we increase the #volatility input, long vannas become shorter, and short vannas become longer and the zero value will shift towards OTM. (The exact shift depends on the Black-Scholes modifications) I coded an animation based on the \"standard\" Black-Scholes formula, that shows you how vega and vanna functions shift if we change the volatility input.\n"},{"ty":"ae","et":"inline","id":"kix.5yu30