quidity, vol can compress. so maybe the price is pinned, but stabile ins a huge positive gamma territory.\nvanna has a complex effect, it is usually have a longer-time frame effect, but vanna is not easy, that will get an individual long post to explain. \ncharm has very little effect usually... it comes into play at the end of the day. and also it is increased if vol is high, especially around the 25 delta strikes. \nmost of the times it is gamma. gamma has an inverse relationship with volatility, and it must be hedged instantly\n\nQ: you mentioned that vol of vol decreasing meaning that traders are rolling their vix positions into March Opex? \nA: it is a very complex reflexive effect. whenever you long an option, you long the vol (bcs you long vega \u003d vol). so if you long a VIX call, you long the vol of VIX.\nBut don\u0027t forget the VIX is the IV of the NEXT 30 days SPX contracts. This is why VIX expo is always 30 days before the SPX expo. So when you long a vix call, you long vanna and vomma on the next 30 days SPX options\nQ: What’s the difference between zero speed and zero weekly?\nA: weekly is based on the net weekly exposure taking the changes into account. it is only to provide a line where the characteristic changes or expected to change\nthis is why i wrote a post on X earlier that i don\u0027t like that many plp try to oversimplify/interpret lvls simply as support or resistance lvls. this is just not true. a lot of lvls we need only to have a pic of characteristic. when the positioning shifts to long to short skew or vice versa territory, you can expect different spot/vol correlation, hedging flows etc. different sentiment\nthe interesting part is when those lvls are \"guarded\" like it was on monday (03 feb) that i wrote in the weekly post, and made me long that down stick and there we go, market rallied\nas said, when you buy an option, you buy vol. you bet on or against the IV on it.\nwhat is vol? the SD of the long returns. what does it mean? 