ssets, as we call them, futures, stocks.. but not true for VIX futs!!!) \nNow if spot moves up by 1 pt, you add the gamma to the delta like: (-50) + (-2) \u003d -52 so the MM became shorter delta, he has to buy 2 more shares of stocks so he buys into the direction. \nif the spot moves down, you simply extract the gamma values from the delta: (-50) - (-2) \u003d -50 +2 \u003d -48 so now, MM only need to have 48 shares of stock, so he will sell 2 shares.  So again, he is hedging into the price direction.\nwhat if you would have sold the same 50 delta call with gamma of 2? now your position would be -50 delta and -2 gamma and the MM would long 50 delta and 2 gamma. so he sells 50 shares of stocks.\nIf spot moves up, his exposure becomes: 50+2 \u003d 52 meaning, he has to sell 2 more.  In this case, he hedges against the price action.  \nif spot moves down, his exposure becomes: 50-2 \u003d 48 meaning, he has to buyback 2. again, hedges against the price movement. selling rips and buying dips. this compresses the ranges.\nthis is a simplified example of how this works. in practice, and in the case of SPX, dealers use ES minis, simply bcs of higher liquidity, futures trades can absorb large orders with less price impact, have lower margin requirements and due to the provided leverage, so dealers can hedge wider notional value trades at once\nthe contract size of ES is $50, this is the quantity of the underlying represented by the fut contract so $50 SPX is $1 ES so if an MM has like 2400 delta, he will sell 2400/50 \u003d 48 ES minis for advanced plp: this is not true for VIX futs thos\nbcs volatility is mean reverting, so VIX futs have no linearity in the underlying index. so the longer-term the contract is the lower its delta is, even \u003c50, but never 1. this makes vol market exciting\nMarket is influenced by the derivative market\nit is all about constant betting. Plp are betting on outcomes with different probabilities on different timeframes, and this creates a feedback loop through the vol market first. i won\u0027t go into it now. \njust think about it: there is a company, and there is a stock of a company. the company has a productivity, performance rate, ... quality in overall, a value, and the stock is meant to \u0027express\u0027/\u0027manifest\u0027 that value but white collars came and they said: lets create derivates on that, like futures to buy the stock at a certain spot at a certain time and bcs the future contract has a different liquidity profile, different supply/demand profile, its pricing can deviate from the actual value of the stock\nso what do I mean? futures are tradeable products. you don\u0027t necessary buy a fut contract bcs you want to buy the stock. you buy it bcs you speculates (like me this morning) and the supply/demand dynamics effect its price but it reflexively creates liquidity on the underlying stock bcs somebody somewhere will buy or sell that stock and there are options another layer of betting\nthe big diff is that here you can exercise it whenever you want (ok, depends on if it is American or European style, but this is not my point now) but! and this is the main thing here options are not one-delta assets this is crucial.\nwhat is delta? it is a rate that shows you how a certain asset follows another one. like a stock is 1 delta, bcs it goes 1:1 with itself. A future is also usually 1 delta, as its value moves together with the underlying (except for VIX futs, bcs of the fluctuating spot/vol correlation) but an option can be 0 to 1 delta multiplied by 100 bcs one contract covers 100 options. So if you buy an 50 delta option, its like buying 50 shares of stocks, if you by a 23 delta option, its like having 23 shares of stocks notionally and this is the true meaning of DEX tho, giving you the notional size of the trade.\n"},{"ty":"as","st":"paragraph","si":28490,"ei":28490,"sm":{"ps_klt_i":true,"ps_awao_i":true,"ps_bb":{"brdr_c2":{"hclr_color":"#000000","clr_type":0},"brdr_s":1.0,"brdr_