Chunk(DOCS_modelChunk); DOCS_modelChunk = undefined;</script><script nonce="EIT3yxRU7NKfkw0Xm3jevw">DOCS_modelChunkParseStart = new Date().getTime();</script><script nonce="EIT3yxRU7NKfkw0Xm3jevw">DOCS_modelChunk = {"chunk":[{"ty":"is","ibi":32565,"s":"But when you buy it, somebody must sell it. and the one who sold you will notionally short sell 50 shares of stocks, so he will have a risk exposure he must hedge it by purchasing 50 shares or futs and so, the key point here is that you already created a situation, when somebody must trade with the underlying asset due to hedging, not bcs of the value of the company and the wild thing is the options on futures... betting on the bet etc. just like in the Big Short movie in the Vegas scene.\nNow bet has a time maturity this is the second dimension of it. simple, right? you bet on that SPX will reach lets say 6050 by friday through long 6050 call. but on friday then, the bet will be closed, and you either won or lost the third one is the standard deviation of the returns, aka volatility.\nagain, simple, right? if the underlying has high volatility (talking about RV), it means that its deviations from the avg are high, price has big moves/swings opposite, when vol is low\nnow... lets say you bet on Monday that SPX will reach 6050 by Friday. SPX currently trading at 6000 in this example. spot has five days to complete the work, and to win the bet. the closer you get to expo, the lower the probability is that you win the bet, bcs you have less and less time each days. if volatility is low, the probability is even lower.  why? bcs you are 50 pts away from your target. if you don\u0027t get big price swing, the likelihood to reach your level is low or even 0... and as an extra, the time is also passing continuously. but if vol is elevated, you have better chance, bcs the price swings are wider.\nnow... market makers are not stupid as the MM sold you that bet, he has significant risk exposure, bcs he will lose it, if you win. He must price the bet in a way to mitigate his risk and this is the risk premium, extra on the fair value. it is also called volatility risk premium, bcs as I said above, the risk comes from volatility:\nif vol goes up, he must ask more for the contract, \nif vol goes down, he is fine with lower price, bcs his risk is lower bcs the probability of you winning the bet changing\nbut we don\u0027t know what the future volatility will be tomorrow, or into friday... we have stoch vol models to assume... but at the end of the day what we get is a tons of bet on the future volatility for the next day, for the day after, for 5 days later etc. this is called IMPLED VOLATILIY\nso if you buy a 6050 5DTE call, you have the strike, the time to expo, spot and risk-free-rate... these four parameters are well defined.\nthe 5th input of the option pricing model is volatility itself, and MMs can play with that now listen very carefully, and i hope you have read my post about betting: if we assume that the market is efficient, we say that plp there have all the necessary infos (insiders included) to estimate the future value of a stock right. so if more and more plp start to bet on this 6050 SPX by friday, the demand of that call contract will elevate.\nwhat does it mean? this means that plp see high probability that the bet will be a winner.\nwhat does it mean for the market maker? it means that he has a significant risk exposure by selling that contract,\nso what will he do? pricing it higher. \nhow? through the volatility input. so the implied vol (IV) of that contract will elevate or in other words: the vol risk premium of that contract will go up, bcs in order to get to 6050 by friday, you need a market with higher weekly vol bcs don\u0027t forget that vol is the SD of logreturns‼️ And by this the premium naturally will elevate on that contract \nthe opposite happens, if we still assume efficient market, and the plp don\u0027t like this bet, and don\u0027t want to bet on 6050 by friday. in this case plp won\u0027t buy that contract, and so the demand for that contract will decrease relative to the supply, so market makers will lower the vol risk premium on it. \nhow? again, changing the vol input but this is not an out-of-nowhere process, and THIS IS KEY! Listen it all depends on WHAT IS THE PREMIUM THAT THE BUYERS ARE WILLING TO PAY FOR THAT BET like in an auction and this will determine the premium, and so the size of the vol risk premium by changing the IV input so this is all reflexive. \n"},{"ty":"ae","et":"list","id":"kix.list.3","epm":{"le_nb":{"nl_4":{"b_gf":"%4","b_ts":{"ts_un":false,"ts_un_i":true,"ts_sc":false,"ts_it_i":true,"ts_fgc2":{"hclr_color":"#000000","clr_type":0},"ts_st_i":true,"ts_bgc2":{"hclr_color":null,"clr_type":0},"ts_fs_i":true,"ts_ff_i":false,"ts_bgc2_i":true,"ts_it":false,"ts_va":"nor","ts_bd_i":true,"ts_va_i":true,"ts_fs":11.0,"ts_ff":"Courier New","ts_st":false,"ts_bd":false,"ts_fgc2_i":true,"ts_sc_i":true,"ts_tw":400},"b_ifl":162.0,"b_gs":"o","b_a":0,"b_sn":1,"b_gt":9,"b_il":180.0},"nl_3":{"b_gf":"%3","b_ts":{"ts_un":false,"ts_un_i":true,"ts_sc":false,"ts_it_i":true,"ts_fgc2":{"hclr_color":"#000000","clr_type":0},"ts_st_i":true,"ts_bgc2":{"hclr_color":null,"clr_type":0},"ts_fs_i":true,"ts_ff_i":false,"ts_bgc2_i":true,"ts_it":false,"ts_va":"nor","ts_bd_i":true,"ts_va_i":true,"ts_fs":11.0,"ts_ff":"Noto Sans Symbols","ts_st":false,"ts_bd":false,"ts_fgc2_i":true,"ts_sc_i":true,"ts_tw":400},"b_ifl":126.0,"b_gs":"●","b_a":0,"b_sn":1,"b_gt":9,"b_il":144.0},"nl_2":{"b_gf":"%2","b_ts":{"ts_un":false,"ts_un_i":true,"ts_sc":false,"ts_it_i":true,"ts_fgc2":{"hclr_color":"#000000","clr_type":0},"ts_st_i":true,"ts_bgc2":{"hclr_color":null,"clr_type":0},"ts_fs_i":true,"ts_ff_i":false,"ts_bgc2_i":true,"ts_it":false,"ts_va":"nor","ts_bd_i":true,"ts_va_i":true,"ts_fs":11.0,"ts_ff":"Noto Sans Symbols","ts_st":false,"ts_bd":false,"ts_fgc2_i":true,"ts_sc_i":true,"ts_tw":400},"b_ifl":90.0,"b_gs":"▪","b_a":0,"b_sn":1,"b_gt":9,"b_il":