ied Vol for week 10-14 Feb\n*\n\n\n\n\n\nDo you remember that I predicted that MMs short vol smile positioning will be realized against customers long vol smile trade? (06/feb intraday post and 07/feb, same pattern) look at this. during the last week (5dP - 5dC range into feb opex)\n*\nFrom intraday post 06 feb\n*\nTo catch the zero vanna effect, you need to look at fix strike vol, not vix or RV\nfix strike vol is basically checking how the vol risk premium changed relative to the expectations earlier.\nCheck skew from your brokerages: check today\u0027s current ATM strike IV and compare it to yesterday\u0027s one\nsame strike, hence fix strike.\n\f\nMonday 10 feb 2025\nI added this note to the yesterday post, bcs i don\u0027t think that this was clear for everybody (from weekly post https://stochvoltrader.substack.com/p/weekly-post-09feb-14feb)\n*\n*\n*\nSPX term structure change into friday, and VIX term structure change into friday both dumped, and as I called last week, the whole vol smile came down and a bit flatter\n*\nrealized basis:\nmarket doesn’t show the steep skew + wide trading ranges that would signal a buildup of crash conditions, despite all those Trump bs … and systematic flows shift to be supportive\n+ the vega supply also creates vol selling from dealers, and retail support are there too, currently market is OK. And this is what GARCH told us in the yesterday post: vol doesn\u0027t really care about the news\n*\nalso I posted on twitter last week the same about VIX GARCH output, that the story is about speculative vol trading now, not about macro concerns, as long as we don\u0027t see skew to get steeper again, and bid on the 5 delta put territory\n-\nQ: When you are working out the puzzle and deciding how much weight to give to skew as opposed to other factors, how are you making that determination?\nA: nice question. always the context. not always the same elements tell the story... i will try to remember examples, but you will see over the time week by week\n-\n\f\n11 feb 2025\nvol down by 2.67% for SPX and and by 2.98% for VIX on a fix strike basis\nskew update for the week. look at those bids on the tails\n *\n For today zero speed at 6137. look at the chart, gamma increases from down to up \u003d positive speed\n*\nSome notes (THANKS TO Ngok996 Alma substack member):\n*\n\nListen.. vanna flips are the strongest daily borderlines. they literally depends on vol, and only on vol. but you must know that intraday, the hedgingflow is determined mostly by gamma. thats the main driver.\nwhen gamma is low, thats where vanna impact comes. and speed profile usually dictates the vol regime.\ni tell you why: if you have a positive speed, it means spot up/gamma up. but it also means, that spot up/vol down, bcs gamma works inversely to vol.\nlogical, bcs when mm is longer gamma, he has to sell more against the price action, that naturally slows down the momentum, compresses the range of returns, and it causes vol to come down.\nOther way to think about it: if gamma is higher on a contract, then its IV will be lower. so if the positioning is longer gamma up, then it is also lower IV.\nif speed is negative, then spot up/gamma down: so if market moves up, less gamma, MMs have to sell less and less against the price (or even buy into the momentum, if they flip negative gamma), so they let vol to expand or even help it to expand. So in a short speed environment, vol naturally goes up if spot goes up.\n"},{"ty":"ae","et":"inline","id":"kix.5tnmrsy8lf9e","epm":{"ee_eo":{"eo_bo":{"ln_s":0,"ln_w":0.0,"ln_c2":{"hclr_color":"#000000","clr_type":0}},"i_pid":null,"eo_mb":9.0,"i_ht":237.0,"eo_rtdf":{"rdf_ft":0},"eo_ml":9.0,"eo_mr":9.0,"eo_ad":null,"i_cid":"s-blob-v1-IMAGE-Lpdh8e-7Tr0","i_cont":0.0,"eo_mt":9.0,"eo_type":0,"eo_lco":{"lc_oi":"","lc_cs":"","lc_ct":0,"lc_sci":"","lc_srk":""},"i_wth":481.8755905511811,"eo_at":null,"i_iwc":{"iwc_w":false},"eo_hb":false,"eo_rtd":"","i_crop":{"crop_oxr":0.0,"crop_oyr":0.0,"crop_rot":0.0,"c