60,"ei":56977,"sm":{"ts_bd_i":false,"ts_bd":true}},{"ty":"as","st":"text","si":57039,"ei":57146,"sm":{"ts_un":true,"ts_un_i":false}},{"ty":"as","st":"text","si":57203,"ei":57274,"sm":{"ts_un":true,"ts_un_i":false}}],"revision":438}; DOCS_modelChunkLoadStart = new Date().getTime(); DOCS_initialLoadTiming.incrementTime('mp', DOCS_modelChunkLoadStart - DOCS_modelChunkParseStart); DOCS_warmStartDocumentLoader.loadModelChunk(DOCS_modelChunk); DOCS_modelChunk = undefined;</script><script nonce="EIT3yxRU7NKfkw0Xm3jevw">DOCS_modelChunkParseStart = new Date().getTime();</script><script nonce="EIT3yxRU7NKfkw0Xm3jevw">DOCS_modelChunk = {"chunk":[{"ty":"is","ibi":57275,"s":"Now... think about it: if you have a zero vanna flip upwards.\nIf MMs are long speed, then they are net long vanna, so above the vanna flip they flip to negative vanna. As said before, if spot moves up in a long speed environment, vol comes down.\nLong vanna \u003d vol down/delta down, triggers more buying, supports the upwards momenutm. But above the flip, it shifts to short vanna, where vol down/delta up... so MMs exposure becomes longer delta, that leads to sudden sell. This is why it can be broken only, if vol starts to move up against gamma. And that behavior is always a result of an anomaly, some sudden increased customer interest of buying vol upthere, and zomma then dumps gammas.\nSame happens, if we are in short speed environment, and we have a vanna flip above us. Vol goes up, as spot moves higher. In negative speed vanna is also net negative, so vol up/delta down, forcing MMs to buy more futs supporting the price. But when the spot reaches the flip, vanna goes from short to long, where high vol pushes deltas up, so MMs switch into selling mode. This is why you have to see vol down against the decreasing gamma in a short speed environment to arrive healthy into a long vanna environment. And this could be a result of customer vol selling interest, naturally increasing gammas through zomma effect.\n-\nbullish MOC coming.. supportive at least + negative charm. real time vol surface:\n*\nas predicted, it is a rangebounding vol trade. you can see some bid on the right wing of the skew, it remained so, but tomorrow I will refresh the skew to check if its still there. to me it tells about some right-tail hedging for tomorrow in the 5d call territory, while atm straddles are still there.\nRV came down, broke below 15% finally, pulling systematics in to buy\n*\nI wanna see the margin of error area broken above during this week, otherwise we decay down into march. i don\u0027t think so, feb opex seems bullish, and atm vol is just shady)\nQ: What does margin of error mean?\nA: so the yellow line is the rolling mean on a volume weighted basis. this gives you an idea where the momentum starts to be stretched and the probability for mean reversion is going up (i plotted 1.5 and 2.5 sigma lvls to provide probability for you) however, as I wrote in my education post about mean reversion, it doesn\u0027t mean that the price retests its mean, but its averages itself down to its mean value, so it will always overshoot the mean. the margin of error area is based on my own experience, it gives you the area that is healthy for the price to stay in, if it breaks the rolling mean. but once it closes out of this area, the directional move is pretty much confirmed.\n-\n\f\nthis was the IV term structure yesterday\n*\nand this is today\n*\nQ: What are the breadth measures you use and are they telling you?\nA: lets call \"A\" the stocks with positive returns, and \"B\" the stocks with negative returns. calculating (A-B)/(A+B) will give you a number in the [-1; 1] range. if the ratio is negative, it means that negative returns start to outweight the positive ones. market with higher breadth means that the movement has momentum and it is less prone to sudden collapse. but if markets showing divergence between this ratio vs the returns, then it foreshadows a reversion. this is breadth basically\n-\n\f\nHere a contribution with some charts (THANKS TO SrLex Alma substack member):\n*\f\n 14 Feb. 25\nQ:Why does \"net short correlation\" mean bullish?\n*\nA: not directly bullish, depends on the context. the article only says that vol is dumping and wil lget sold. when investors short correlation, long dispersion, they pin index vol. they buy vol at certain assets and sell vol on the otherside. if markets are at ATH, low vol logically stabilizes it on those lvls + vanna/charm tailwind\n-\nQ: When we touched the zero vanna line today, was it important to watch how IV and vol reacted at this point? To give us a hint as to if price would be supported here?\nA: Vanna is all about vol. this is why i keep telling, that what is the vol condition that makes a vanna flip weak or strong. check my description of vanna in the OD chat first. when vanna flips the whole delta/vol relationship flips (non instantly, but it is a very strong aggressive effect) and the delta hedging turns 180°\n"},{"ty":"ae","et":"inline","id":"kix.8owumiph4r3u","epm":{"ee_eo":{"eo_bo":{"ln_s":0,"ln_w":0.0,"ln_c2":{"hclr_color":"#000000","clr_type":0}},"i_pid":null,"eo_mb":9.0,"i_ht":251.48036547433907,"eo_rtdf":{"rdf_ft":0},"eo_ml":9.0,"eo_mr":9.0,"eo_ad":null,"i_cid":"s-blob-v1-IMAGE-AxrvC8pxlGU","i_cont":0.0,"eo_mt":9.0,"eo_type":0,"eo_lco":{"lc_oi":"","lc_cs":"","lc_ct":0,"lc_sci":"","lc_srk":""},"i_wth":340.425,"eo_at":null,"i_iwc":{"iwc_w":false},"eo_hb":false,"eo_rtd":"","i_crop":{"crop_oxr":0.0,"crop_oyr":0.0,"crop_rot":0.0,"crop_hr":1.0,"crop_wr":1.0},"i_iw":false,"i_rot":0.0,"i_clst":{"cv":{"op":"set","opValue":[]}},"i_bri":0.0,"i_msct":0,"i_src":"","i_opa":1.0}}},{"ty":"ae","et":"inline","id":"kix.99id7b275ml6","epm":{"ee_eo":{"eo_bo":{"ln_s":0,"ln_w":0.0,"ln_c2":{"hclr_color":"#000000","clr_type":0}},"i_pid":null,"eo_mb":9.0,"i_ht":223.0,"eo_rtdf":{"rdf_ft":0},"eo_ml":9.0,"eo_mr":9.0,"eo_ad":null,"i_cid":"s-blob-v1-IMAGE-OVVwhwrcSew","i_cont":0.0,"eo_mt":9.0,"eo_type":0,"eo_lco":{