_initialLoadTiming.incrementTime('mp', DOCS_modelChunkLoadStart - DOCS_modelChunkParseStart); DOCS_warmStartDocumentLoader.loadModelChunk(DOCS_modelChunk); DOCS_modelChunk = undefined;</script><script nonce="EIT3yxRU7NKfkw0Xm3jevw">DOCS_modelChunkParseStart = new Date().getTime();</script><script nonce="EIT3yxRU7NKfkw0Xm3jevw">DOCS_modelChunk = {"chunk":[{"ty":"is","ibi":61548,"s":"the key is to know what is the vanna convexity and what territory is beyond the zero vanna: positive or negative.\n·   \tif positive, you need relatively high vol to break through the zero vanna,\n·   \tif negative, you need relatively low vol to break through the flip.\njust think about that... the reason is delta hedging. and also it is totally contractionary what the speed profile would indicate, and this is why we have to watch the \"hidden\" effects too, that i described this morning\n\n\n19 Feb 2025\nFrom weekly post (feb17-21)\n*\n*\nSkew\ni will cover skew in depth later in educational posts, but the key is that smirk is caused of the increased leverage and left-tail hedging at the OTM put wings.\nOTM contracts do have higher IV than ATM, but skewed to left-tail hedges.\nSmirk examines the IV along the moneyness, with the same maturity. We have different smirks for each maturities, and we want to know the slope to see the supply/demand ratio changes over the time (how the bets move).\nThe OTM vs ATM (smile) curvature decay by expiration, so it is more pronounced for near-dated options\nskew is basically the slope of the smirk on different segments\n*\nyou basically measures this\nand by knowing how the slope changes, you can see how the supply/demand changes.. hedging behaviour. we can examine it on a fixed delta basis, where we get the certain delta strikes on each maturity, or fixed strike basis... fixed strike shows us how the smirk shifts, just like fix strike vol\nfixed delta shows us how the supply/demand for i.e. 22delta puts changes\n*\nbut if you fix the strikes, and take the same strikes for each maturity, you will see how the smirk moves over the time\n*\n this is the key idea behind fix strike vol, smilira with fix strike skew\nand this is why VIX is not the fear index, bcs it looks at the atm, and it naturally moves up or down as market moves. I will cover formulas in the dedicated post, but this is the main idea\nso when we look at the skew curves, we have to think in 3 dimension\n-\nSo longer skew…\nlook at this... the 22dP/22dC teeter-totter can be steeper not only if the puts are bid, but when calls are offered.\nthink about this: if 22dP goes down relative to the ATM (middlepoint), but still, 22dP/22dC is steeper, then it is due to bcs not the put IV goes up, but bcs call IV goes down\nthink in 3 dimensions, same thing with shorter skew\n-\n\nSPEED\nso you asked about longer speed above 5700 gamma drop. So speed is the slope of the curvature. The speed is still negative there, but approaches zero, so it goes up (longer).\nimagine that you slips a tangent line on the gamma curve and constantly measuring the angle of the tangent line due to x-axis, it will decrease\n\n\n \n \n \n \n \n \n *\n\nQuestion about color flip.. nice logic, but i talked only about NET color flip, not the exact zeros. color and charm flips are very unlikely to be at the same spot, bcs color is basically the charm convexity due to spot. so where charm has max or min, color has zero. i used that to measure how steeply the positive charm exposure will fade to the upside.\n-\nQuestion about small caps. have you read my educational post about market theory (efficient market)? I wrote it for you. smaller the market cap, higher the potential return too, but i like more predictable vol profile, this is why i focus mainly on SPX. I know it, can read it well, and it can provide high returns on intraday basis, just like anything else, but i take less risk, bcs I have a better chance to read it good\nbut to answer your question, liquidity premium can compress when market conditions are stable (see Fama–French three-factor model). in a controlled vol environment this liquidity premium might not widens that much, allowing small caps to perform better relative to larger caps. Also, empirically deregulation favors for them, as it reduces costs for smaller firms. Also note, that the beta of small caps can be higher, telling that if vol environment is stable, they can provide alpha in the short-run. Tech led positive momentum can provide spillover effect on small caps. this is why rotation occurs, and long dispersion, short correlation, short vol.\n"},{"ty":"ae","et":"inline","id":"kix.2sdcbtcbi3u3","epm":{"ee_eo":{"eo_bo":{"ln_s":0,"ln_w":0.0,"ln_c2":{"hclr_color":"#000000","clr_type":0}},"i_pid":null,"eo_mb":9.0,"i_ht":245.0,"eo_rtdf":{"rdf_ft":0},"eo_ml":9.0,"eo_mr":9.0,"eo_ad":null,"i_cid":"s-blob-v1-IMAGE-xa-sYcBhrVQ","i_cont":0.0,"eo_mt":9.0,"eo_type":0,"eo_lco":{"lc_oi":"","lc_cs":"","lc_ct":0,"lc_sci":"","lc_srk":""},"i_wth":481.8755905511811,"eo_at":null,"i_iwc":{"iwc_w":false},"eo_hb":false,"eo_rtd":"","i_crop":{"crop_oxr":0.0,"crop_oyr":0.0,"crop_rot":0.0,"crop_hr":1.0,"crop_wr":1.0},"i_iw":false,"i_rot":0.0,"i_clst":{"cv":{"op":"set","opValue":[]}},"i_bri":0.0,"i_msct":0,"i_src":"","i_opa":1.0}}},{"ty":"ae","et":"inline","id":"kix.85nbmth4vb4i","epm":{"ee_eo":{"eo_bo":{"ln_s":0,"ln_w":0.0,"ln_c2":{"hclr_color":"#000000","clr_type":0}},"i_pid":null,"eo_mb":9.0,"i_ht":381.0,"eo_rtdf":{"rdf_ft":0},"eo_ml":9.0,"eo_mr":9.0,"eo_ad":null,"i_cid":"s-blob-v1-IMAGE-ucPiSp8jZf8","i_cont":0.0,"eo_mt":9.0,"eo_type":0,"i_wth":481.8755905511811,"eo_lco":{"lc_oi":"","lc_cs":"","lc_ct":0,"lc_sci":"","lc_srk":""},"eo_at":null,"i_iwc":{"iwc_w":false},"eo_hb":false,"eo_rtd":"","i_crop":{"crop_oxr":0.0,"crop_oyr":0.0,"crop_rot":0.0,"crop_hr":1.0,"crop_wr":1.0},"i_rot":0.0,"i_iw":false,"i_clst":{"cv":{"op":"set","opValue":[]}},"i_bri":0.0,"i_msct":0,"i_src":"","i_opa":1.0}}},{"ty":"ae","et":"inline","id":"kix.cw4m1z685du1","epm":{"ee_eo":{